{"id":"2001.07245","submitter":"Evandro V. L. de Mello","authors":"E. V. L. de Mello","title":"A framework for the description of charge order, pseudo and\n  superconducting gap, critical temperature and pairing interaction in cuprate\n  superconductors","comments":"5 pages, 5 figures","journal-ref":"Journal of Physics Condensed Matter 32, 2020","doi":"10.1088/1361-648X/ab9fd5","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.supr-con","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A unified phenomenological description framework is proposed for the\nevaluation of some of the most important observables of the cuprate\nsuperconductors: the pseudogap (PG) $\\Delta_{\\rm PG}$, the local\nsuperconducting amplitudes $\\Delta_{\\rm SC}(r_i)$, the critical temperature\n$T_{\\rm c}$ and charge ordering (CO) parameters. Recently detailed measurements\nof CO structures and CO wavelengths $\\lambda_{\\rm CO}$ are faithfully\nreproduced by solutions of a Cahn-Hilliard differential equation with a free\nenergy potential $V_{\\rm GL}$ that produces alternating small charge\nmodulations. The charge oscillations induce atomic fluctuations that mediate\nthe SC pair interaction proportional to the $V_{\\rm GL}$ amplitude. The local\nSC amplitude and phase $\\theta_i$ are connected by Josephson coupling $E_{\\rm\nJ}(r_{\\rm ij})$ and the SC long-range order transition occurs when ${\\left <\nE_{\\rm J} \\right>} \\sim k_{\\rm B}T_{\\rm c}$. The calculated results of the\nwavelength $\\lambda_{\\rm CO}$, $\\Delta_{\\rm PG}$, $\\left < \\Delta_{\\rm\nSC}\\right >$ and $T_{\\rm c}$ calculations are in good agreement with a variety\nof experiments.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 20 Jan 2020 20:40:04 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 14 Jul 2020 18:36:15 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-07-16"}
