{"id":"2001.08056","submitter":"Jesse van Oostrum","authors":"Jesse van Oostrum","title":"Bures-Wasserstein geometry for positive-definite Hermitian matrices and\n  their trace-one subset","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Information Geometry (2022) pp. 1-17","doi":"10.1007/s41884-022-00069-7","report-no":null,"categories":"math.ST stat.TH","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In his classical argument, Rao derives the Riemannian distance corresponding\nto the Fisher metric using a mapping between the space of positive measures and\nEuclidean space. He obtains the Hellinger distance on the full space of\nmeasures and the Fisher distance on the subset of probability measures. In\norder to highlight the interplay between Fisher theory and quantum information\ntheory, we extend this construction to the space of positive-definite Hermitian\nmatrices using Riemannian submersions and quotient manifolds. The analog of the\nHellinger distance turns out to be the Bures-Wasserstein (BW) distance, a\ndistance measure appearing in optimal transport, quantum information, and\noptimisation theory. First we present an existing derivation of the Riemannian\nmetric and geodesics associated with this distance. Subsequently, we present a\nnovel derivation of the Riemannian distance and geodesics for this metric on\nthe subset of trace-one matrices, analogous to the Fisher distance for\nprobability measures.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 21 Jan 2020 11:19:48 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sat, 24 Sep 2022 11:21:16 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-09-27"}
